<a name="Leven"><hr></a>
<br>
<table width=100%><tr>
<td width=80%>
<font color=green>
<h4><u>Loch Leven and the River Leven : a Landscape Transformed</u></h4>
<font color=black>
<p>
Author:&nbsp; <font color=red>David Munro<font color=black>. &nbsp; Ref: WOLL
</p>
<p align=justify><font color=maroon>
From its source at the south-east corner of Loch Leven, Scotland's most famous trout fishing loch, the River Leven flows 16 miles through Fife and Kinross to meet the Firth of Forth at Leven. &nbsp; A fall of 300 feet between loch and sea attracted industry to its banks in the 18th century, and for over a hundred years the River Leven was the most utilised stretch of water in Scotland. &nbsp; This book describes how the water from both river and loch has been used and abused by landowners and industrialists, and in particular focuses on one of Scotland's greatest civil engineering schemes, which entailed the construction of a four-mile-long channel, the building of sluice gates, and the lowering of Loch Leven by 4.5 feet between 1828 and 1832. &nbsp; Designed to provide a constant supply of water to over 40 mills on the River Leven, the Leven Improvements had a dramatic impact on the landscape. &nbsp; The full story of this scheme, which is told here for the first time, reveals an intriguing catalogue of disasters, errors and personal conflicts. &nbsp; The pre- and post-drainage landscapes are described, and the story is brought up to date, tracing the struggle to control the quantity and quality of water flowing out of Loch Leven and down what was for many years described as Scotland's most polluted river.
</p>
<p>
<b><font color=black>
Price direct from RSGS:&nbsp; &pound;10.00.<br>
RSGS members' price:&nbsp; &pound;8.00 (excluding postage and packing).<br>
</b>
</p>
