<br>
<table width=100% cellpadding=5><tr>
<td width=100% colspan=2>
<font color=green>
<h4><u>The Voyage of the <i>Scotia</i> : the story of Scotland's forgotten Polar heroes</u></h4></td>
</tr><tr>
<td width=20% valign=top>
<img src="images/voyascot.jpg" alt="Voyage" width=164 height=240>
</td>
<td>
<p>
Authors: <font color=red>R.H. Rudmose Brown, J.H. Pirie, R.C. Mossman.<font color=black>
</p>
<p>
First edition 1906;&nbsp; new edition 2002, with foreword by Dr <font color=red>David Munro.
</p>
<p align=justify><font color=maroon>
This timely re-issue of the story of the Scottish expedition, on the centenary of <font color=indigo><i>Scotia</i></font>'s voyage, makes enthralling reading. &nbsp; As Dr David Munro, Director of the Royal Scottish Geographical Society, says in his new Foreword, 'it has all the elements of a tale of high adventure, describing as it does the rigours of life at sea, the trials of overwintering in Antarctica, and the highs and lows of morale ebbing and flowing with the icy waters of the South Atlantic'.
</p>
<p align=justify>
Like all the best explorers' tales, this account of <font color=indigo><i>Scotia</i></font>'s voyage is full of hardships, danger and spectacular, never-before-seen vistas. &nbsp; Despite the modesty of the authors, it graphically depicts the courage, physical endurance and mental toughness of the Scots who boldly sailed into unknown seas.
</p>
<p><font color=black>
<b>Price direct from RSGS:&nbsp; &pound;12.99 (ref. <u>WOVS)</b>
</p>
</td></tr></table>
